# Tailwind CSS Preference Rule

## Always Use Tailwind CSS

**PREFER Tailwind CSS classes over inline `style` attributes whenever possible.**

### When to Use Tailwind:
- ✅ Layout (positioning, spacing, sizing)
- ✅ Colors (background, text, border)
- ✅ Typography (font size, weight, family)
- ✅ Spacing (padding, margin)
- ✅ Flexbox/Grid layouts
- ✅ Responsive design (breakpoints)
- ✅ Z-index, opacity, transforms

### When to Use Inline Styles:
- ❌ Only when Tailwind doesn't have a direct equivalent
- ❌ Dynamic values that require JavaScript calculations
- ❌ Complex calculations or conditional styling based on runtime data
- ❌ CSS properties not available in Tailwind (use `style` as fallback)

### Examples:

**✅ GOOD - Use Tailwind:**
```tsx
<div className="absolute top-4 left-4 bg-black text-white p-4 rounded">
  Content
</div>
```

**❌ BAD - Avoid inline styles:**
```tsx
<div style={{ position: 'absolute', top: '16px', left: '16px', background: 'black', color: 'white', padding: '16px', borderRadius: '4px' }}>
  Content
</div>
```

**✅ GOOD - Use style for dynamic values:**
```tsx
<div className="absolute bg-black" style={{ top: `${calculatedTop}px`, left: `${calculatedLeft}px` }}>
  Content
</div>
```

### Migration Strategy:
When editing existing code:
1. Replace inline styles with Tailwind classes
2. Keep `style` only for dynamic/calculated values
3. Use `clamp()` and responsive values with Tailwind's responsive utilities when possible
